{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d789a8d3-327c-4c1c-8dbe-5a546d69f20e","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's a summary:\n\n## 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test-ID generation strategy**. Every test gets a new ID, so ADO treats them as new. To restore history, add a `.runsettings` file (or update your existing one) that forces the legacy strategy:\n\n```xml\n<RunSettings>\n  <MSTest>\n    <TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n  </MSTest>\n</RunSettings>\n```\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level** context — it's no longer tied to a specific test. Accessing `TestName` now throws. Fix your code like this:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is no longer available here in v4\n    // Use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName instead, or\n    // move per-test logic to [TestInitialize]\n}\n```\n\n## 3. Other key v4 breaking changes to watch for\n\n| Area | What changed |\n|---|---|\n| **Class/Assembly init inheritance** | `[ClassInitialize]` / `[ClassCleanup]` now default to `InheritanceBehavior.BeforeEachDerivedClass` (was `None`). Base-class init runs for every derived class. |\n| **Assert.ThrowsException** | Now checks for the **exact** exception type; derived types no longer match. Use `Assert.ThrowsExactly` or catch the base type explicitly. |\n| **Parallel execution** | Parallelism defaults changed; review `[Parallelize]` settings if you see new race conditions. |\n| **`[DataRow]` with `null`** | `[DataRow(null)]` handling was tightened — explicit cast may be needed: `[DataRow((string?)null)]`. |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | Some legacy properties were removed from the dictionary. |\n\nThe inheritance behavior change (#3, row 1) is the one that silently breaks the most projects — base-class `[ClassInitialize]` methods suddenly fire in derived test classes where they didn't before.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"996ad379-466f-4940-892e-35fd618af2bd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me address their specific issues:\n\n1. **Tests appearing as brand new in Azure DevOps (no history)**: In MSTest v4, the default test ID generation strategy changed. MSTest v3 used a \"legacy\" test ID scheme, while v4 uses a new default. This changes the test IDs, so Azure DevOps sees them as entirely new tests. The fix is to set `<TestIdGenerationStrategy>` in the `.runsettings` file to use the legacy strategy, or accept the new IDs.\n\n2. **`TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]` throwing**: In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is no longer associated with a specific test method (since it's class-level initialization). \n\nAccessing `TestName` throws because there's no individual test context available at that point—this is a breaking change from v3 where it was somewhat accidentally exposed.\n\n3. **Other things to watch out for**: `[ClassInitialize]` and `[ClassCleanup]` inheritance behavior changed, `TestContext` properties like `TestName` aren't available in class-level fixtures, default timeout behavior may have shifted, `DeploymentItem` behavior changed, and parallel execution defaults might differ.\n\nThe key MSTest v4 changes are the fully qualified test name format affecting test IDs and ADO test history, the `TestContext` behavior in `[ClassInitialize]` where `TestName` is no longer populated, inheritance behavior defaults for class-level attributes now being `BeforeEachDerivedClass`, stricter type checking in `Assert.ThrowsException`, and changes to how `DataRow` handles null values.","outputTokens":1148},"id":"3ba49301-37f5-4f3f-bcb9-4152191ef5f1","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:04:59.497Z","parentId":"5480fd86-3e2a-4a9f-9053-0e2abac3ce03"}
